{{Infobox company | name = Phamaly Theatre Company | logo = | type = [[Non-profit]] | industry = [[Entertainment]] | genre = [[Theatre]] / [[Disability]] | foundation = 1989<!-- this parameter modifies "Founded" --> | founder = | location_city = [[Denver]], [[Colorado|CO]] | location_country = [[United States]] | location = <!-- this parameter modifies "Headquarters" --> | key_people = | area_served = Denver Metro | homepage = [http://www.phamaly.org www.phamaly.org] | footnotes = }}
'''Phamaly Theatre Company''' (formerly the '''Physically Handicapped Actors & Musical Artists League''' or '''PHAMALy'''), also known as just '''Phamaly''' (as in "family"), is a theater group and touring company based in [[Denver, Colorado]] formed entirely of people with disabilities from across the spectrum.{{r|Moore-2015}} Phamaly was founded in 1989 by a group of former students of the Boettcher School, a now-closed school for the disabled.{{r|ACA}} The students were frustrated with the lack of theatrical opportunities for people with disabilities and wanted to create a theatre company that provided those individuals with the opportunity to perform.{{r|about}} Phamaly Theatre Company performs primarily at the [[Denver Performing Arts Complex]] and the Aurora Fox Theatre.{{r|where}} The company's season also includes various touring and educational shows. Its recent seasons have seen productions tour outside the state of Colorado into neighboring Wyoming as well as [[Osaka, Japan]].{{r|Moore-2015}}
==Recognition== Phamaly Theatre Company has gained national attention and has received numerous local awards, including the Mayor's Award for Excellence in the Arts{{r|AVD}} and Theatre Company of the Year from [[5280 Magazine]] and the Alliance for Colorado Theatre.{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=March 2016}} Phamaly's 2005 production was awarded two Ovation Awards from the [[Denver Post]], including Best Musical and Best Director, was recognized by the [[Rocky Mountain News]] as one of ten best productions of the year, and was named top overall show by the [[Boulder Daily Camera]].{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=March 2016}} At the 2008 [[Henry Awards]] (Denver's version of the [[Tony Award|Tonys]]),{{r|Flomberg-2015}} Phamaly won four awards with ''Urinetown, the Musical'', for Outstanding Actress in a Musical (Juliet Villa), Outstanding Lighting Design (Stephen D. Mazzeno), Outstanding Choreography (Debbie Stark, Cindy Bray) and Outstanding Direction of a Musical (Steve Wilson).{{r|Calhoun-2008}}
On August 29, 2006, Phamaly was featured in a lengthy segment of ''[[The News Hour with Jim Lehrer]]'' on [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]].{{r|Bowser-2006}} This marked the company's first mainstream national publicity. Previous to that, Phamaly is also the subject of a documentary short entitled ''We Are PHAMALY'' directed by [[Daniel Junge]].{{r|Crosetto-Garcha-Horan-2009}} Long-time company member Mark Dissette made a feature-length documentary, ''There's Still Hope for Dreams (A PHAMALy Story)'' (2008).{{r|DFS}}
Phamaly was honored to receive grants for community impact from the [[National Endowment for the Arts]] in 2013 and 2014.{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=March 2016}}
==Productions== Phamaly performs a musical every summer, usually in the Space Theatre at the [[Denver Performing Arts Complex]].{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=March 2016}}
In January 2007, the company opened the first non-musical production in its history at the Aurora Fox Theatre on historic [[Colfax Avenue]]. The company has performed at the Aurora Fox every winter since. In 2011 it expanded to the [[Arvada Center for the Arts and Humanities]] as well.{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=March 2016}}
Since the fall of 2008, Phamaly has also produced a series of sketch comedy productions entitled ''Vox Phamalia''. These cabaret style shows consist of original comedic, dramatic, and musical material written in a workshop over several weeks before being performed.{{r|Moore-2011}} The 2011 version&nbsp;– ''Vox Phamalia: Quadrapalooza''&nbsp;– received numerous awards and nominations from Denver theatre critics, including one for Best Director for Edith Weiss, who originated the Vox Phamalia series.{{r|Moore-2011b}}
2012 saw the start of another original comedy series titled ''disLabled'' which marked the company's debut appearance in the city of [[Boulder, Colorado]] and recurred for two years in 2013 and 2014.{{r|CPR-disLabeled}}
Throughout its history, Phamaly has also had a number of touring productions consisting of original and previously produced pieces. These productions have been performed at schools, corporate events, community gatherings, and resort venues. Since 2012, Phamaly has had a regular touring series of children's theatre productions that has traveled all over [[Colorado]] and [[Wyoming]].{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=March 2016}}
==Phamaly Success Stories== Two members of Phamaly&nbsp;– Regan Linton and Jason Dorwart&nbsp;– have gone on to earn, respectively, a Master of Fine Arts in Acting and a PhD for Theatre and Drama, both through the [[University of California, San Diego]].{{r|Holicky-2015}}{{r|UCSD-Dorwart}} Linton went on to become the first wheelchair user to be cast as a company member of the [[Oregon Shakespeare Festival]] and currentky serves as Phamaly's Artistic Director. Dorwart is now a Visiting Assistant Professor of Theater at [[Oberlin College]]. {{r|Holicky-2015}} In addition, Laura Alsum, one of the original Vox Phamalia actors/writers completed the Masters program for screenwriting at UCLA where she won the Tribeca Sloan Student Grand Jury Prize for Screenwriting.{{r|Guerrasio-2014}} Long time Phamaly member Lucy Roucis was featured doing her stand up comedy act about [[Parkinson's Disease]] in the 2010 romantic comedy ''[[Love & Other Drugs]]''.{{r|Moore-2010}} Long time company member Jeremy Palmer earned his MFA in Screenwriting from the [[University of Southern California]] and also went on to win the Tribeca Sloan Student Grand Jury Prize in 2018.
==Production History (1990-2015)== Previous productions have included:{{r|productions}} {{div col|colwidth=25em}} * ''[[Guys and Dolls (musical)|Guys and Dolls]]'' (1990) * ''[[Oklahoma!]]'' (1991) * ''[[Anything Goes]]'' (1992) * ''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]'' (1993) * ''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]'' (1994) * ''[[How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying]]'' (1995) * ''[[A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum]]'' (1996) * ''[[Mame (musical)|Mame]]'' (1997) * ''[[The Boy Friend (musical)|The Boy Friend]]'' (1998) * ''[[Side Show]]'' (1999)<ref>{{cite web |last=Lillie |first=Jim |title=Step Right Up |work=Westword |url=http://www.westword.com/issues/1999-07-15/culture/theater.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050218234918/http://www.westword.com/issues/1999-07-15/culture/theater.html |archivedate=February 18, 2005}}</ref> * ''[[Grand Hotel (musical)|Grand Hotel]]'' (2000) * ''[[Damn Yankees]]'' (2001) * ''[[Once Upon a Mattress]]'' (2002){{r|Crosetto-Garcha-Horan-2009}} * ''[[The Pajama Game]]'' (2003) * ''[[Guys and Dolls (musical)|Guys and Dolls]]'' (2004) * ''[[Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat]]'' (2005) * ''[[The Wiz]]'' (2006){{r|Bowser-2006}} * ''[[Our Town]]'' (2007) * ''[[Urinetown: the Musical]]'' (2007) * ''[[One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest (play)|One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest]]'' (2008) * ''[[Side Show]]'' (2008)<ref>{{cite web |last=Wittman |first=Juliet |date=June 12, 2008 |title=Side Show |work=Westword |url=http://www.westword.com/arts/side-show-5099294 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160327000237/http://www.westword.com/arts/side-show-5099294 |archivedate=March 27, 2016 |deadurl=no}}</ref> * ''[[Vox Phamalia: Tales from the Crips]]'' (2008) * ''[[Stand Up for Democracy]]'' (2008) * ''[[Steel Magnolias]]'' (2009) * ''[[Man of La Mancha]]'' (2009) * ''[[Vox Phamalia: Redux]]'' (2009) * ''[[Barefoot in the Park]]'' (2010) * ''[[Beauty and the Beast (musical)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' (2010) * ''[[Vox Phamalia: Triage]]'' (2010) * ''[[The Diviners (play)|The Diviners]]'' (2011) * ''[[How to Succeed In Business Without Really Trying]]'' (2011) * ''[[Vox Phamalia: Quadrapalooza]]'' (2011){{r|Moore-2011}}{{r|Moore-2011b}} * ''[[The Elephant Man]]'' (2012) * ''Cyrano'', an adaptation by Joe Roets of ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'' (2012 touring production)<ref>{{cite news |last=Kleinman |first=Jessica |date=September 10, 2012 |title=Phamaly Presents: Cyrano de Bergerac |department=Theatre |work=303 Magazine |url=http://303magazine.com/2012/09/phamaly-presents-cyrano-de-bergerac/ |accessdate=November 15, 2014}}</ref> * ''[[disLabled]]'' (2012) * ''[[Little Shop of Horrors (musical)|Little Shop of Horrors]]'' (2012) * ''[[Vox Phamalia: Cinco de Vox]]'' (2012) * ''[[The Foreigner (play)|The Foreigner]]'' (2013) * ''[[disLabled: Improvise, Adapt, & Overact]]'' (2013) * ''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]'' (2013){{r|Kennedy-2013}} * ''[[Vox Phamalia: G.I.M.P. Nation]]'' (2013) * ''[[It's a Wonderful Life]]'' (2013) * ''[[The Velveteen Rabbit]]'' (2013 touring production) * ''[[The Glass Menagerie]]'' (2014) * ''[[disLabled: Disorderly Conduct]]'' (2014){{r|CPR-disLabeled}} * ''[[Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat]]'' (2014) * ''[[Vox Phamalia: Pity Pity Bang Bang]]'' (2014) * ''[[Rapunzel]]'' (2014 touring production) * ''[[The Fantasticks]]'' (2015) Toured to Osaka, Japan{{r|Moore-2015}} * ''[[Cabaret]]'' (2015) {{div col end}}
